defaultHow robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report? Have the IPCC adequately addresse
defaultd
default criticisms of previous reports? How much scope is there to question the report’s conclusions? 
default6.
default              
defaultIt is our view that the AR5 WG1 report represents a robust evaluation of the available scientific literature. 
defaultA key part of the IPCC assessment is to disting
defaultuish 
defaulthigher confidence
default conclusions from the more unresolved aspects of our 
defaultscientific understanding 
defaultof the climate system and climate change
default in which confidence is lower
default. The distinction is made within the IPCC report by its use of terminology that reflect
defaults quantitative levels of likelihood and scientific confidence. On the whole, we believe that the adopted terminology adequately reflects the level of scientific consensus that prevailed at the time the report was written. The fact that a large component of
default recent climate change is a consequence of human-driven changes in atmospheric composition is an example of a robust conclusion. In contrast, 
defaultgaps in scientific knowledge limit our confidence in predictions of future regional precipitation changes. 
default&#xa0;
default7.
default              
defaultSo
defaultme c
defaultriticisms of previous Working Group I reports focused on the review process, and the 
defaultimportant 
defaultrole of review editors
default in overseeing the review process
default has been re-affirmed
default in AR5
default. Government review comments have again played a strong part in improving 
defaultupon the second-order draft.  
