default What 
defaultareas need further effort to reduce the levels of uncertainty?
default10.
default              
defaultMany of the basics of climate science (such as the fact that increased levels of greenhouse gases will lead to a warming of the climate system) had been established in earlier assessments
default and so 
defaultare 
defaultconsidered largely settled
default.
default There is sufficient confidence in many of the observed changes in the climate since 1950 for these to be presented as facts.
default 
defaultLike many scientific areas, progress in climate science is steady and incremental, so it is
default difficult to identify 
defaultnew 
defaultareas which have be
defaultcome
default completely settled in AR5
default WG1
default, although many areas were identified in which confidence in our understanding had increased
default, for example
default the attribution of the warming since 1950 to anthropogenic causes
default. It 
defaultis important to stress that IPCC assessments do not do research, but rather 
defaultreport research that is already available in the scientific literature. There is a multitude of areas where further research, by the community as a whole, is required to reduce unc
defaultertainty. These include the continued need to monitor the climate system, the role of cloud feedbacks in determining the magnitude of climate change, the role of aerosol particles in modifying cloud properties
default,
default and the need to improve confidence in more re
defaultgional-scale climate predictions. This list is by no means exhaustive.
defaultHow effective is AR5 and the summar
defaulty for policymakers in conveying
default what is meant by 
defaultuncertainty in scientific terms
default? Would a focus on risk rather than uncertainty be useful?
default11.
default 
defaultAR5 WG1
default, including its 
defaultSummary for Policymakers (SPM)
default, 
defaultuse
defaults
default 
defaultclearly and carefully defined
default language to express uncertainty through a combination of scientific confidence and likelihood. Scientific confidence is expressed as being low to very high, depending upon t
defaulthe amount of available evidence and the level of agreement between multiple lines of evidence. Where likelihoods have been estimated these are expressed using terms such as ‘very uncertain’, ‘likely’ and ‘virtually certain’ which correspond to specific pro
defaultbability ranges. We believe this combination of qualitative and quantitative measures is an effective means of conveying the uncertainty in the scientific conclusions of the AR5 
defaultWG1
default, given the diverse nature of the scientific evidence being assessed.
default&#xa0;
default12. If risk is interpreted to mean the likelihood of an outcome which is considered to be of high consequence, then any of the likelihood statements of the AR5 
defaultWG1 
defaultthat refer to thresholds can be straightforwardly translated into statements of risk. For ex
defaultample, the 
defaultAR5 
defaultWG1 
defaultSPM
default statement that cumulative carbon emissions need to be kept below 1000 PgC in order for global warming relative to pre-industrial times to likely not exceed 2
default
defaultC, implies that there is a 33% risk of global warming exceeding 2
default
defaultC under t
defaulthese conditions. Since the likelihood statements in the AR5 
defaultWG1 
defaultare all based on probabilistic calculations, it should in principle be straightforward to obtain risks of exceeding particular thresholds from those calculations. However, the AR5 only estimat
defaulted likelihoods for statements where the scientific confidence is fairly high. This reflects the conservative nature of the assessment, since it would not have been possible to obtain a consensus on likelihoods of outcomes where the scientific confidence is
default fairly
default low. 
defaultFor example, the likelihood of
default increases in intense tropical cyclone activity, or increases in intensity and/or duration of drought, 
defaultwas not assessed in the near-
defaultterm; 
defaultfor the long-term 
default(end of the 21
defaultst
default century)
default the likelihood of such increase
defaults 
defaultwas only
default assessed in certain regions of the world, and without quantifying
default the extent of the 
defaultlikely increases
default. Yet policy-makers are presumably interested in such risks, because the consequences would be significant. Assessment of risk in areas where sci
defaultentific confidence is low would therefore be useful, but would probably have to come from a 
defaultmechanism other than the IPCC.
