defaultHas AR5 
defaultsufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?
default14.
default              
defaultThe widely reported hiatus in 
defaultthe rise in 
defaultglobal 
defaultmean 
defaultsurface temperature was a rapidly developing research topic while the AR5 
defaultWG1 
defaultwas being
default written. While there were certainly many papers to assess, the topic was nowhere near as mature as most of the other topics covered in the report. Furthermore the observations of ocean heat content and radiative forcing were not adequate to obtain a compl
defaultete picture, given the short time scale of the phenomenon from a climate perspective. On the topic of the hiatus the AR5 
defaultW
defaultG
default1 
defaultwas essentially forced to serve as a climate bulletin, dealing with a breaking event, which is not what it was designed to do. Unde
defaultr these circumstances the AR5 authors 
defaultadequately assesse
defaultd
default the scientific evidence available at the time
default, recognizing that the picture would almost certainly evolve in the future. 
defaultIs the IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scientific knowledg
defaulte? Or has it focussed on providing a justification for political commitment?
default15.
default              
defaultThe IPCC scientific assessments are a large-scale undertaking. Author teams, and especially the co-ordinating lead authors, are committed to prolonged and deep involvement (vi
defaulta successive lead author meetings, through various cycles of producing draft chapters and via the need to respond to the many review comments). Thus it requires these scientists, and their employing institutes, to take on this significant workload. 
default&#xa0;
default16.
default              
defaultT
defaulthe resulting assessment chapters are certainly comprehensive in their coverage of their area, describe in detail how the area has evolved since the previous assessment, and discuss where the most important uncertainties remain. The chapters remain an impor
defaulttant resource for the scientific community for many years after they are produced.  In that sense, they certainly are highly effective, recognizing the effort required to produce them is immense. 
default&#xa0;
default17.
default              
defaultWe note that the IPCC assessments do differ from criti
defaultcal reviews of the scientific literature as would be produced by (normally) small author teams and mediated by the standard peer review procedure used by learned journals. In that case, authors have much more freedom to define the scope of their reviews an
defaultd are able to be more radical and forthright in their assessment and critique of the literature. By contrast, in order to carry entire chapter teams together, and to satisfy the many review comments, IPCC assessments are normally more consensual and conser
defaultvative in their nature. 
default&#xa0;
default18.
default              
defaultAs part of the preparations for the recent assessments, the community has also voluntarily undertaken large-scale intercomparisons of both observational datasets and outputs from climate models, generated by many institutes ac
defaultross the world. These intercomparisons have generated much new information, pointed to areas where understanding is robust
default. They have also
default provided a stimulus and motivation for understanding the differences that emerge from these intercomparisons, a proce
defaultss that lasts for many years following the assessment.  Without the impetus of the IPCC assessments it is unlikely that these intercomparisons would be so comprehensive. An example of the value of the intercomparisons is that projections of the patterns of
default future temperature change are quite robust amongst climate models but, by contrast, the projections of patterns of precipitation change are not. The intercomparison process places a significant burden on the science community. For the next assessment, it 
defaultwill be important to assess 
defaultwhether the scope of future intercomparisons could be scaled back to make them more manageable, so that resource is not distracted away from other activities in the individual institutes. 
default&#xa0;
default19.
default              
defaultThe assessments present policy-rel
defaultevant advice, and the policymakers provide input on the overall structure of the reports
default and review drafts
default. However they do not dictate the nature of any policy-relevant advice that emerges from the process, which is based, as it should be, on the prevaili
defaultng scientific view at the time of the assessment. 
defaultTo what extent did political intervention influence the final conclusions of the AR5 Physical Science Basis summary? 
default20.
default              
defaultPolicymakers were able to input review comments to the second-order draft and in th
defaulte final plenary sessions in Stockholm
default in September 2013
default. We believe that on the whole, this input was a positive one that led to greater clarity of presentation in the conclusions, and the wide spectrum of political viewpoints would have prevented any over
defaulttly political influence from one sector.
default We are not aware of any evidence that political intervention influenced the final conclusions. 
