defaultWhat implications do the IPCC’s conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report have for policy making both nationally and internationally? 
default21.
default              
defaultThe IPCC AR5 Working Group I report concludes that there is more convincing evid
defaultence that humans are influencing the climate than was available at the time of the AR4 in 2007. This is based not only on longer series of observations, but also on a larger body of refereed literature. The report also concludes that continued emissions wi
defaultll cause further warming and that
default any efforts to 
defaultlimit climate change will require substantial and sustained reductions of greenhouse gas emissions. These conclusions are also phrased in stronger language than in AR4. Correcting for the different baseline 
defaultperiod, the AR5 mean estimate of change in temperature at the end of the 21
defaultst
default century under the highest forcing (RCP8.5) is very similar to the highest change presented in AR4. 
defaultThe mean estimate of the temperature change using the lowest forcing in AR5 (us
defaulting RCP2.6) is lower than the lowest 
defaultmean 
defaultchange in AR4, 
defaultbut this is because the lowest emissions pathways considered explicitly assume very stringent controls on emissions – unlike the lowest scenario used in AR4.
defaultIs the rate at which the UK Government 
defaultintends to cut CO
default2
default emissions appropriate in light of the findings of the IPCC AR5 Physical Science Basis report? What relevance do the IPCC’s conclusions have in respect of the review of the fourth Carbon Budget? 
default22.
default              
defaultThe 
defaultIPCC 
defaultAR5 
defaultWG1 report
default has progressed by including results from advanced carbon cycle models that simulate the budgets of carbon in the atmosphere, land vegetation and soil, and the ocean. The only scenario presented in which it is likely that 
defaultglobal average surface 
defaulttemperature
default rises will remain below 2 degrees was the most stringent (RCP2.6). The carbon cycle models confirm that very large decreases in global carbon emissions, declining to around or below zero by the end of the century, are needed for this scenario. The corresp
defaultonding maximum total carbon 
defaultemission to achieve this goal is
default 1000 GtC of which 445 to 585 GtC have already been emitted. Thus the latest science 
defaultfrom the IPCC reconfirms the scientific evidence that was available at the time the 4th carbon budget was set.
